Deployment models: public, private, hybrid, and multi-cloud.

This is a separate question from the service model. The service model was how much you manage. The deployment model is where the infrastructure actually lives.

Public cloud is provider-owned and multi-tenant. You share physical hardware with other customers, but you're isolated logically. This is the default for everything in this course.

Private cloud is single-organization infrastructure: dedicated hardware, no other tenants. You see it where regulation or policy demands it, like banks, government, and sensitive workloads. On AWS this shows up as Outposts and Dedicated Hosts.

Hybrid connects a public cloud to private or on-premises infrastructure over a dedicated link, such as a V-P-N or Direct Connect. Most large enterprises live here during and after a migration. Some systems stay on-premises, and the rest run in AWS.

Multi-cloud spreads workloads across more than one public provider, like AWS plus Azure or Google Cloud. The usual reasons are avoiding vendor lock-in, or using a specific service that only one provider offers.

For the exam, and for most real work, public is the default. The others are each an answer to a specific constraint: data residency, latency to on-premises systems, or avoiding lock-in.
